SIMPLE: snug
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Snug
<hw>Snug</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos>
<adjf>Snugger</adjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos>
<adjf>Snuggest</adjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</amorph> <ety>[Prov. E.
<ets>snug</ets> tight, handsome; cf. Icel. <ets>sn⟦oum⟧ggr</ets> smooth,
ODan. <ets>sn⟦oum⟧g</ets> neat, Sw. <ets>snugg</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Close and warm; <as>as, an infant lies
<ex>snug</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Close; concealed; not exposed to notice.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Lie <qex>snug</qex>, and hear what critics say.</q>
<rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Compact, convenient, and comfortable; <as>as, a
<ex>snug</ex> farm, house, or property</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Snug</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Snug
<hw>Snug</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Mach.)</fld> <def>Same as
<er>Lug</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, 3.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Snug</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Snug
<hw>Snug</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Snugged</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Snugging</conjf><pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <def>To lie close; to
snuggle; to snudge; -- often with <xex>up</xex>, or <xex>together</xex>;
<as>as, a child <ex>snugs</ex> up to its mother</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Snug</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Snug
<hw>Snug</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To place snugly.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark> <rj><au>Goldsmith.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To rub, as twine or rope, so as to make it smooth
and improve the finish.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Snuggery</ent>⟦br⟧
